modules.description: This module provides arithmetic operations on integers and floats with custom operators for addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division, along with constants like pi and pi2. It includes utility functions for angle conversion between degrees, radians, and turns, as well as a clamp function for restricting values within a range. These functions are used for numerical computations in geometry, physics simulations, and graphics rendering.

Handles key press and release events with string-based key identifiers. Provides functions to check if a key is currently pressed, register event handlers for specific keys, and clear registered handlers. Useful for implementing keyboard input logic in interactive applications like games or command-line interfaces.

This module implements a set data structure with operations to create an empty set, insert elements, and remove elements. It works with generic elements of any type `'a`, maintaining uniqueness and efficient membership checks. Concrete use cases include tracking unique identifiers, managing permissions, or filtering duplicates from a sequence.

This module defines a color type with hexadecimal and RGB representations, providing constructors for common colors like red, green, blue, and gray shades. It includes a function to clamp integer values to valid RGB ranges. Use this module to represent and manipulate colors in graphics or UI applications where precise color definitions are required.

This module handles conversions between POSIX time and millisecond timestamps. It provides functions to convert an integer millisecond value to a floating-point POSIX timestamp and vice versa. Useful for interfacing with systems that expect time in different formats, such as JavaScript APIs or low-level system calls.

This module provides operations for managing immutable collections of ordered elements, supporting efficient membership checks, insertions, deletions, and set-theoretic operations like union and intersection. It works with balanced binary trees that maintain elements in sorted order, offering logarithmic-time complexity for key operations. Typical use cases include maintaining unique element collections, performing range queries, and leveraging sorted data structures for tasks like priority queues or ordered traversals.
